I"B<h2 id="launch-your-exocore">Launch your Exocore</h2>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>If you don’t have a Github account, <a href="https://github.com/join">create one here</a>. Git provides the ability to edit your project locally, and push it to the web to be deployed as a website.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Launch your Exocore instance on Netlify in a few minutes by clicking <a href="https://app.netlify.com/start/deploy?repository=https://github.com/hot-domme/exocore">here</a>. Netlify offers free hosting for your Exocore, and builds your site server-side with Jekyll. Sign up with your Github account, and follow the instructions to create a new Git repository (project) from this template. You’ll end up on a ‘Site Overview’ page from which you can customize your domain name (in domain settings).</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>Your Exocore is now live! Read on to find out how to edit it on your local machine.</p>

<h2 id="local-exocore-setup">Local Exocore setup</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Clone your new repository to your device</li>
</ol>

<p>Now that you have <a href="https://github.com/join">signed up with Github</a> and published your template Exocore, the easiest way to get the repository onto your device is to use the Github GUI. You can also use the command line tool, but the GUI is friendlier for new users. You can download the <a href="https://desktop.github.com/">here</a>.</p>

<p>and click the ‘Use this template’ button on <a href="https://github.com/hot-domme/exocore">this repo</a>, then follow the instructions. If you are unfamiliar with Git, you can take a look at the <a class="wiki-link" href="/articles/installation-instructions/#appendix-using-git-for-the-first-time">appendix</a> at the bottom of the page.</p>

<h3 id="3-download-vscode">3. Download VSCode</h3>
<p>[VSCode]](https://code.visualstudio.com/) is a program you can use to write posts in your Exocore with the help of some handy <a class="wiki-link" href="/articles/exocore/#full-tech-stack">recommended extensions</a>.</p>

<h3 id="4-open-your-newly-forked-repository-in-vscode">4. Open your newly forked repository in VSCode</h3>
<p>Open VSCode and click file &gt; Open, then navigate to your Exocore’s root directory.</p>

<p>Your Exocore is now ready to be edited locally. You can learn about how to create new posts <a class="wiki-link" href="/articles/start-here/#creating-new-posts">here</a>, or get familiar with Exocore syntax <a class="wiki-link" href="/articles/syntax/">here</a>.</p>

